<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1912-04-06T23:36:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1912-04-06T23:36:00-05:00" n="1031" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1031">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 812.00/3519.</note>
                        <head ana="#head_untitled-inferred-from-preceding-sibling-head">[Untitled]</head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">American Embassy</hi>, <lb/>
                                    <hi rend="italic">Mexico</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1912-04-06T22:00:00-06:36">
                                    <hi rend="italic">April 6, 1912—10 p.m.</hi>
                                </date>
                                <lb/> (Received April 7, 1912—1 p.m.)</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>A tremendous ovation for De la Barra, just arrived. He is speaking in
                            favor of peace and maintenance of law and order, but is rather vague in
                            his attitude toward the Government.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Wilson.</hi>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>